A Nyquist plot of clean printed carbon electrode (PCE), modified with GO/PCE and CuONPs/GO/CDot(N)/PCE nanostructures (Fig. 7
                        ), was obtained by plotting the sum of resistance (real components) vs inductance and capacitance (imaginary components). The fit of height plus the semi-circular curve of the semicircle (height and width) can obtain the charge transport resistance (Rct), which measures the resistance charges during transport from the liquid phase (electrolyte) to the solid phase (surface electrode and modified electrode surface) [70]. As can be seen in Fig. 8
                         (regular and enlarged), the electrode modified with CuONPs/GO/CDot(N) nanostructures showed better electron transfer at the electrode solution interface (Rp = 344 Ω) compared with GO (Rp = 936 Ω) and clean PCE (Rp = 385 Ω). The best charge transport process on the electrode-electrolyte interface presented by the CuONPs/GO/CDot(N) nanostructures electrode is due to the better conductive character resulting from the synergistic effect between homogenous CuO nanoparticles onto graphene oxide sheet and CDot(N), resulting in a more significant number of electroactive sites. The respective circuit can be seen in Supplementary Figure S1.

CuONPs/GO/CDot(N) nanostructures formation has occurred by direct reaction between Cu(NO3
                     )
                     2, GO, and CDot(N) and has been characterized by HR-TEM micrographs, XRD, Raman, UV-vis, and XPS spectroscopies. HR-TEM micrographs showed homogeneous dispersion of CuONPs onto the GO surface, and the PCE modified with CuONPs/GO/CDot(N) nanostructures has presented low detection limits and good sensitivity compared to other modified electrodes because of the presence of copper nanostructure that makes complex linkage with glyphosate molecules. The excellent synergistic effect between GO, CuONPs, and CDot(N) makes of the CuONPs/GO/CDot(N) nanostructures have presented good electrocatalytic properties in determining glyphosate in real samples in the presence of other pesticides.
